      <hedline>
        <hl1>Metro Business; Casino Plan Approved</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Steve Strunsky</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Strunsky, Steve</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>New Jersey Casino Control Commission approves four-year license renewal and bankruptcy restructuring plan for Sands Casino Hotel, Atlantic City; cites Carl C Icahn's infusion of $65 million in cash and bankruptcy court approval of plan (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The New Jersey Casino Control Commission approved a four-year license renewal and bankruptcy restructuring plan yesterday for the Sands Casino Hotel in Atlantic City.</p>
        <p>The key to the restructuring is the involvement of financier Carl C. Icahn. The commission gave him interim permission in May to acquire a 65 percent stake in the Sands, which sought protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code in 1998.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>The New Jersey Casino Control Commission approved a four-year license renewal and bankruptcy restructuring plan yesterday for the Sands Casino Hotel in Atlantic City.</p>
        <p>The key to the restructuring is the involvement of financier Carl C. Icahn. The commission gave him interim permission in May to acquire a 65 percent stake in the Sands, which sought protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code in 1998.</p>
        <p>A spokesman for the commission said Mr. Icahn's infusion of $65 million in cash and a restructuring plan that has already been approved in bankruptcy court, assured the commissioners that the Sands could be stable.</p>
        <p>Steve Strunsky</p>
      </block>
